    "rationale": "The oxidation of 1-butanol to butanal is a simple, clear, and canonical textbook example of the Swern oxidation. It demonstrates the conversion of a primary alcohol to an aldehyde without over-oxidation to a carboxylic acid, which is a key feature of this reaction. The reactants and products are acyclic, small, and lack complex functional groups, making it an ideal, unambiguous representation of the core transformation.",
    "collision_avoidance_note": "This example uses a simple primary aliphatic alcohol, avoiding aromatic rings (which could trigger Friedel-Crafts or other electrophilic aromatic substitution queries), complex stereocenters, or other reactive functional groups. The choice of 1-butanol specifically avoids ethanol (too simple, might be confused with industrial processes) and benzyl alcohol (avoids aromatic ring collisions). This ensures the query is highly specific to the Swern oxidation of a primary alcohol."
  }
}
